  "signature": "ed25519:9c9747295c29d23f9af715b058fd2b8176fd28c8b15062c4eae3cff3e77764ea2724a916a5da8c8ca07e7d31eca72b2e35ee7741d022ac3ee3bb649288e8600e",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-sqa-criteria",
      "rationale": "ABAQUS 2022 (Dassault Systèmes) used as the FEA solver. Software is FDA-recognized and holds ISO 9001:2015 certification. Internal SQA plan documented version control (Git, tagged release v3.1.2), regression test suite (47 benchmark cases, all passing), and configuration management records. All simulation scripts archived in institutional repository with hash-verified checksums. SQA level exceeds MRL 3 requirement.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-sqa-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ncv-criteria",
      "rationale": "Code verification performed against three ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems: Hertzian contact between elastic cylinders (analytical solution), thick-walled cylinder under internal pressure (Lamé solution), and large-deformation neo-Hookean block compression (published reference solution). ABAQUS solutions matched analytical references to within 0.3% in all cases. Patch test for C3D8I elements confirmed convergence. Results documented in verification report NCV-2024-03.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-ncv-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-disc-criteria",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study conducted on three systematically refined meshes (coarse: 42,000 elements; medium: 168,000 elements; fine: 672,000 elements) using Richardson extrapolation. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for peak contact stress: GCI_fine = 1.8%, GCI_medium = 7.2%, confirming asymptotic convergence (ratio 3.96 ≈ 4, consistent with second-order elements). Production mesh (medium refinement) selected; discretization error contribution to peak contact stress bounded at ±2.1%. Contact surface seeded at 0.25 mm maximum element edge length.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-disc-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-testcond-criteria",
      "rationale": "Bench validation experiments conducted under ISO 14243-1:2009 compliant conditions: axial force profile (0–2600 N), flexion-extension kinematics (0–58°), internal-external rotation (±6°), and anterior-posterior translation (±5 mm) all applied via servo-hydraulic knee simulator. Environmental conditions (37°C phosphate-buffered saline lubricant, pH 7.4) maintained and logged throughout testing. Test protocol reviewed and approved by institutional biomechanics laboratory. Cadaveric specimens (n=6 fresh-frozen, age 55–72, BMI < 30) prepared per ASTM F2083 guidelines. Boundary conditions in FEA replicate test fixture constraints to within documented tolerance.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-testcond-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-outcomp-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison between FEA predictions and experimental measurements performed using three metrics: (1) normalized contact stress ratio CSR (mean 0.98, all 18 tests within ±12% of unity); (2) contact area relative error (mean 6.3%, max 11.8%); (3) centroid location of peak stress region (mean offset 1.4 mm, max 2.9 mm). Statistical equivalence established via two one-sided t-tests (TOST, α=0.05, equivalence margin ±15%). All three QoIs pass equivalence criteria. Uncertainty in experimental reference (film calibration ±8%) explicitly accounted for in comparison. Exceeds MRL 3 requirement by demonstrating multi-metric statistical equivalence.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-outcomp-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-qoi-criteria",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI (peak contact stress on tibial insert articulating surface) is directly linked to clinical wear outcomes via the Archard wear law, which is the mechanistic basis for UHMWPE wear prediction in regulatory submissions (FDA Guidance Document 2017-D-3673). Secondary QoIs (contact area, stress centroid location) are established surrogates for wear pattern fidelity documented in peer-reviewed literature. Traceability matrix maps each QoI to the COU acceptance criterion (CSR < 1.15) and to the device risk assessment. QoI selection reviewed and endorsed by clinical orthopedic surgeon consultant.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-qoi-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-valrel-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities span the COU envelope: bench tests replicate ISO 14243 gait loading (the regulatory standard for knee implant wear testing), cadaveric experiments provide in situ bone-implant interface boundary condition fidelity, and material characterization tests were conducted on the same GUR 1050 UHMWPE production lot used in the clinical device. The validation hierarchy progresses from material coupon to component to system level, consistent with ASME V&V 40 Section 6. Gaps between validation conditions and COU (in vivo vs. in vitro lubrication, patient-specific anatomy variability) are explicitly documented and bounded via sensitivity analysis.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-valrel-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-nse-criteria",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence verified for all 6 gait loading configurations: Newton-Raphson equilibrium residual norm < 1×10⁻⁴ N (force) and < 1×10⁻⁵ m (displacement) for all increments. Contact penetration tolerance set to 0.001 mm; augmented Lagrangian contact algorithm used to enforce non-penetration constraint. No solution divergence or spurious hourglassing detected. Time integration accuracy assessed by halving the increment size for one representative configuration; peak contact stress changed by 0.4%, confirming temporal discretization error is negligible. All convergence logs archived.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-nse-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-useerr-criteria",
      "rationale": "Independent analyst review conducted by a second FEA engineer not involved in model development. Review checklist (37 items) covered boundary condition assignment, material property input, contact pair definitions, reference frame consistency, and load application sequence. Three minor discrepancies identified (unit inconsistency in one material card, incorrect reference node for kinematic coupling in draft model, missing tie constraint at bone-cement interface in revision 1) and corrected prior to final analysis. All corrections documented in issue tracker. Final model reviewed and signed off by principal investigator. Use error probability assessed as low given structured review process.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-useerr-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-modelform-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model form assumptions documented and justified: (1) Ogden hyperelastic constitutive model for UHMWPE selected over linear elastic based on material characterization data showing nonlinear response above 4 MPa contact stress (within COU operating range); (2) cortical and cancellous bone modeled as linearly elastic with orthotropic material properties derived from CT-based density mapping (Keyak et al. regression); (3) cement layer modeled as isotropic linear elastic (E = 2.5 GPa); (4) frictionless contact at femoral component–insert interface supplemented by sensitivity analysis with μ = 0.04 (lubricated) and μ = 0.08 (boundary lubrication) showing peak stress variation < 3.5%. Model form uncertainty contribution estimated at ±6% of peak contact stress via structured sensitivity analysis across plausible constitutive model alternatives.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-modelform-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-modelinputs-criteria",
      "rationale": "Input uncertainty quantification performed via Latin Hypercube Sampling (n=500 samples) propagating uncertainty in: UHMWPE elastic modulus (CV 8%), Ogden strain energy coefficients (CV 5%), cortical bone modulus (CV 12%), cancellous bone modulus (CV 18%), and applied gait load magnitude (CV 6%, based on published inter-subject variability). Output uncertainty in peak contact stress: mean 12.4 MPa, 95th percentile 15.1 MPa (21.8% above mean). Sensitivity indices (Sobol first-order) indicate UHMWPE modulus (38%) and cancellous bone modulus (29%) as dominant contributors. All input distributions documented with source references (manufacturer data sheets, published literature, and experimental characterization). Input dataset version-controlled and hash-verified.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-modelinputs-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-testsamples-criteria",
      "rationale": "Bench validation used 6 tibial insert specimens from the same production lot as the clinical device (lot number TKR-2023-0441, GUR 1050 UHMWPE, gamma-irradiated 25–40 kGy in nitrogen). Specimen dimensional inspection confirmed all within ±0.05 mm of nominal geometry (CMM measurement). Cadaveric specimens (n=6) represent the target patient population (age 55–72, BMI 22–29, no prior knee surgery, no metabolic bone disease). Sample size justified via power analysis: 80% power to detect 15% difference in peak contact stress at α=0.05 requires n=5 specimens; n=6 provides margin. Specimen characterization data archived and linked to validation dataset.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-testsamples-evidence"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-equivinputs-criteria",
      "rationale": "Equivalency between validation test inputs and COU model inputs assessed across all major parameter categories. Geometry: FEA mesh generated from CT scan of production-equivalent device; bench specimens from same production lot — equivalency confirmed. Loading: ISO 14243 gait profiles used in both bench test and COU FEA; inter-laboratory load profile comparison shows < 2% deviation in peak force and < 1° deviation in peak flexion angle. Material: same GUR 1050 UHMWPE lot used for bench specimens and material characterization test coupons; material property inputs directly derived from coupon test data. Boundary conditions: FEA fixture constraints validated against bench test fixture compliance measurements (tibial tray rotation < 0.1° under maximum load). Residual input equivalency gaps (in vivo lubrication vs. PBS, patient anatomy variability) documented and bounded by sensitivity analysis with < 8% impact on peak contact stress.",
      "evidence": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/nagaraja-ortho-equivinputs-evidence"
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-ortho-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-ortho-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for the tibial insert contact stress FEA model (COU1, MRL 3) is accepted based on the following structured evidence review. All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed and all achievedLevel values meet or exceed the requiredLevel for MRL 3. Key findings supporting acceptance: (1) Software quality assurance: ABAQUS 2022 with full SQA plan, version control, and regression testing — achievedLevel 3 exceeds requirement of 2. (2) Code verification: Hertzian contact and Lamé benchmarks verified to < 0.3% error. (3) Discretization error: GCI analysis confirms peak contact stress discretization error bounded at ±2.1%, within the ±5% MRL 3 threshold. (4) Validation results: Three independent validation activities (bench pressure film, cadaveric strain gauge, material characterization) all pass their respective acceptance criteria. The primary QoI (contact stress ratio CSR) achieved mean 0.98 with all 18 test replicates within the CSR < 1.15 acceptance criterion; statistical equivalence confirmed via TOST. (5) Model form uncertainty (±6%) and input parameter uncertainty (95th percentile 21.8% above mean) are quantified and within acceptable bounds for the COU decision consequence (HIGH) and model influence (MEDIUM) combination at MRL 3. (6) Independent analyst review identified and corrected three use errors prior to final analysis, reducing use error risk to low. (7) Test sample equivalency confirmed between validation specimens and clinical device production lot. (8) The validation activity hierarchy spans material, component, and system levels, providing comprehensive coverage of the COU operating envelope. The structured evidence chain is complete: all ValidationResults link to experimental datasets, generating activities, and uncertainty quantification records. No unresolved weakeners or open issues remain. The credibility assessment team unanimously recommends acceptance of the model for the stated COU.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
